<br>
There seem to be 2 complains to your post.  One - is the criminal justice system in general (i.e., new trial), and two, the death penalty.<br>
<br>
I don't support the death penalty.  My primary reason is that it is simply applied unfairly and recklessly in this country.  It is undeniable that whether you die or get life often times hinges on what race you are, or the race of your victim, i.e., if you are are black you are gonna fry, and if you kill a white women you are gonna fry.  To me that is insane.  Time and again statistics show that death hinges not on the facts, but how you look.  Good looking kid from the suburbs who did a horrible murder? You get life.  Ghetto lookin &quot;gangsta&quot; from compton - death.<br>
<br>
Another problem with the death penalty is that undoubtedly innoncent people are executed.  You just can't take it back. The former gov of illinois (who was republican)  communted ALL death row convictions to life, because people were just shocked at how DNA evidence was freeing wrongly conficted folks.<br>
<br>
HOWEVER, with that said, I might be for the death penalty if they took out the subjectivity into how it is applied, i.e., if you did it -death - no jury to decide if you die or live.  As a proud liberal this might seem strange to some, but again, I just hate how death penalty is applied.  If they applied it fairly, I probably would be for it.<br>
<br>
As for the criminal justice system in general - its the best around - but crap happens.<br>
<br>
Californai courts and the 9th circuit are the most liberal courts in the country.  I doubt they'll change the slow death penalty cases on the west coast, because basically, the west coast on the whole is not as gung ho for the death penalty as those in the south are.<br>
