<br>
However, the point you are making is to criticize the justice system.  I disagree.  I believe that the system we have now is one of the best in the world (with the exception of the barbaric death penalty).  <br>
<br>
My reasons are this.  Justice is vengeance and I do see a problem with vengeance.  We do not live under the law of Moses though I hear a lot of right-wing fanatics advocating that we do.  <br>
<br>
I once was dumbfounded to watch a preacher on television in a &quot;Family Bible Study Hour&quot; reading from Deuteronomy(sp) about how when a wife talks back she should have her hand cut off;  the preacher's elaboration during this &quot;Family&quot; show was that due to modern laws we unfortunately just simply cannot do this (but we should hold to the principal).  Thats a big wtf.  Back to the issue and away from conservative ideals, revenge solves nothing unless it is a serious civil trial in which tangible monetary damage have been done.  <br>
<br>
We could be like isolated tribes in Africa that periodically wipe themselves out by avenging family member's deaths until no one is left alive.  When does the vengeance stop?  When you kill a death row inmate you are still taking away someone's family member.  If we kill criminals for the &quot;sake&quot; of the victim's family, then we are right back to square one.<br>
<br>
And of course we *must* be more civil than those Muslims that beat their women and kill criminals on a whim.  Actually their laws and punishments are more grounded in social and religious ideals rather than skewed justice beliefs we have.  I can at least respect Islamic criminal law as it has remained unchanged for so long.  Someone steals, cut off their hand, they cant steal with it again.  Makes more sense than spending $1,000's sending a teenager to bootcamp for a $2 candy bar shoplift.  Perhaps those examples are too extreme though.<br>
<br>
Finally, the &quot;fucked up&quot; justice system.  Is it wrong that we would rather let 1 guilty man go free than imprison 100 innocents?  No, it is not.  It was set up this way hundreds of years ago and has been interpreted liberally ever since so that we may avoid a facist criminal justice system.  Hundreds of death row innmates in the last few years with DNA technology have been absolved.  The system is not without flaw.  Oh, but at least we catch &quot;some&quot; guilty people right?  What if you, or a loved one was that person wrongly convicted or railroaded through the courts to make a political or social statement?  That could never happen you say?  Yea, you are probably right as long as you are not a black male age 18-35.<br>
<br>
